{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5f471c1d-b128-4e16-85c3-affe69d6ce7f","content":"\n\nRun **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is exactly what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but won't pull newer workload manifests needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after that, also try:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload restore   # installs any workloads declared in your project\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fd7b6af2-e03b-4b48-925a-57854567235b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":240},"id":"15640a00-5b24-400b-9169-61ec57cfac43","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:45:46.481Z","parentId":"70c72df7-cbe6-43ac-b91c-c6fb31c37a50"}
